<exercise checkit-seed="0000" checkit-slug="L4" checkit-title="Argument Analysis with Tables">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Consider the following argument.
            <ul>
                <li>Premise 1: if it is hot today, then it is false that class is cancelled.</li>
                <li>Premise 2: class is cancelled.</li>
                <li>Conclusion: it is false that it is hot today.</li>
            </ul>
            First translate this multi-line argument into the long implication that describes it in pure logic. Clearly state how you are assigning the variables P, Q, and possibly R. Then determine if the argument is valid using a truth table. Make sure your table is in the standard order.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p> First off, in symbols the argument is
            <ul>
                <li>Premise 1: <m>P \rightarrow  \sim Q</m></li>
                <li>Premise 1: <m>Q</m></li>
                <li>Conclusion: <m> \sim P</m></li>
            </ul>
        This means that the long implication that describes the argument is <m>((P \rightarrow  \sim Q) \wedge (Q)) \rightarrow ( \sim P)</m>. The truth table for that is below.</p>
        <m>
        \begin{array}{llcc} P &amp; Q &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; ((P \rightarrow  \sim Q) \wedge (Q)) \rightarrow ( \sim P) \\ \hline \text{T} &amp; \text{T} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{T} \\ \text{T} &amp; \text{F} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{T} \\ \text{F} &amp; \text{T} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{T} \\ \text{F} &amp; \text{F} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{T} \\ \end{array}
        </m>
        <p>The argument is valid by because all of the entries in the final column of the truth table are true.</p>
    </answer>
</exercise>
